<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06247122 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06247122 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FRUIT; FARM; WOMAN; DEATH; OBITUARY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  When Marianna Sorci came to the Santa Clara Valley by train via Ellis Islandin 1919, there wasn't even a streetlight to be found.;   Seventy-two yearslater, traffic signals abound -- as well as the fruits of her labor.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MARIANNA SORCI, FRUIT GROWER, 84  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Obituaries  </MEMO><TEXT>     Mrs. Sorci, 84, died of natural causes Friday in San Jose. She and herhusband, Frank Sorci, owned and operated orchards in the Almaden, CambrianPark and Evergreen areas of San Jose. Many of the trees are still standing.;  &quot;She loved to see things grow, whether it was roses in her yard or the apricottrees she tended,&quot; said her daughter, Dorothy Mauro of San Jose.;   BornMarianna LaCorte in Bageria, Sicily, she came to the United States at age 12accompanied by her mother, sister and brother to join their father, who hadimmigrated four years before. They were detained several days at Ellis Islanduntil they could provide proof of support.;   Afterward, Mrs. Sorci joined herfather at a ranch in Mountain View.;   She married in 1936. During the summermonths, their children and grandchildren worked together to help cut and dryapricots and process prunes.;   &quot;They taught us to be hard workers. My mothermade sure everyone did their jobs properly,&quot; Mauro said.;   The Sorcis retiredfrom ranching in 1985, but continued to own and operate commercial propertiesin San Jose, Santa Clara and Fremont.;   Mrs. Sorci was a member of the theItalian Catholic Federation and the Willow Glen Senior Citizens Club.;MARIANNA SORCI; (box)Born: July 19, 1907, Bageria, Sicily.; (box)Died: Aug.30, 1991, San Jose, Calif.; (box)Survived by: Husband, Frank Sorci of SanJose; children, Phyllis Chappell, Anna Mae Piro, Dorothy Mauro and Mary AnnCrannell, all of San Jose; 11 grandchildren; and 10 great-grandchildren.;(box)Services: Vigil and rosary were Monday at Lima Family-Erickson Mortuary.Services today at Lima Family Mortuary, 710 Willow St., then to St.Christopher's Church for a 10 a.m. Mass. Burial follows in Santa Clara MissionCemetery.; (box)Memorial: Donations may be made to the O'Connor HospitalFoundation's Hospice Program.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910903  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  340  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, September 3, 199100247122,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>